    "body": "For a single package: \r\n``` bash\r\n# spack buildcache list\r\n==> Finding buildcaches in <MIRROR_ROOT>/build_cache\r\n==> Fetching file://<MIRROR_ROOT>/build_cache/linux-centos7-x86_64-gcc-4.8.5-xextproto-7.3.0-v5vttf7jlxd4lkqhrtc4x5zflbudgpov.spec.yaml\r\n######################################################################## 100.0%\r\n==> Enter\r\nspack buildcache install /v5vttf7\r\n to install \"xextproto@7.3.0%gcc@4.8.5 arch=linux-centos7-x86_64 \"\r\n```\r\n\r\n```buildcache list``` will print two lines for each new spec discovered, then three more lines for each package. I think a better output would look similar to ```spack find``` output. The download output isn't useful for someone that wants a list of available packages.\r\n\r\n``` bash\r\n# spack find -lv --show-full-compiler zlib\r\n==> 1 installed packages.\r\n-- linux-centos7-x86_64 / gcc@4.8.5 -----------------------------\r\n64vg6e4 zlib@1.2.11%gcc@4.8.5+optimize+pic+shared\r\n```",
